metadata.title: HYPOSPACE: EVALUATING LLM CREATIVITY AS SET-VALUED HYPOTHESIS GENERATORS UNDER UNDERDETERMINATION

abstract.Background/Problem: Scientific problems are often underdetermined with multiple valid hypotheses for the same observations, but current LLM evaluations focus only on single correct answers.
abstract.Method/Approach: Introduces HypoSpace, a diagnostic suite that treats LLMs as hypothesis samplers and measures Validity, Uniqueness, and Recovery across three structured domains with exact enumeration.
abstract.Innovation: Provides deterministic validators and enumerated ground truth to measure LLM creativity in exploring multiple non-redundant hypotheses, revealing mode collapse invisible to correctness-only metrics.
abstract.Limitation/Future Work: The framework is instantiated in structured domains with deterministic validators; future work may extend to less structured problems and broader hypothesis spaces.

Conclusion.Set-Valued Evaluation Suite: A diagnostic suite for evaluating LLMs under underdetermination, featuring exact validators and enumerated valid sets for structured tasks.
Conclusion.High Validity, Limited Uniqueness: Frontier models show high Validity but limited Uniqueness and Recovery as the admissible set of hypotheses expands.
Conclusion.Quantitative Performance Collapse: The observed decline in VR/NR/RR metrics is quantitative and measured against enumerated ground truth, not anecdotal.
Conclusion.Diagnostics as Controlled Probe: These diagnostics serve as a controlled probe set for developing methods to map admissible hypothesis spaces in LLMs.

Methodology & Setup.Hypothesis Space Definition: The framework defines a full hypothesis space H and a subset H_O consistent with observations O, requiring soundness, completeness, and controllability of H_O size.
Methodology & Setup.Sampling and Evaluation Protocol: Models generate N independent hypothesis samples, with N often set to |H_O| to enable coverage analysis and recall-at-k metrics.
Methodology & Setup.Diagnostic Task Instances: Three structured tasks are used: causal graph inference from perturbations, 3D voxel reconstruction from projections, and Boolean genetic program synthesis.
Methodology & Setup.Validity and Distinctness Checks: Each proposal is checked for validity against observations and distinctness from prior samples using task-specific canonicalization methods.

Context & Related Work.Underdetermined Scientific Inference: Many scientific problems have multiple valid explanations for the same data, requiring systems to explore the full set of admissible hypotheses rather than finding a single correct answer.
Context & Related Work.HypoSpace Evaluation Framework: A diagnostic suite operationalizing creativity theory with three metrics: Validity (consistency), Uniqueness (non-redundancy), and Recovery (coverage of the admissible hypothesis set).
Context & Related Work.Controlled Diagnostic Tasks: Three structured domains with exact enumeration of valid hypotheses: causal graphs, 3D voxel reconstruction, and Boolean genetic interactions, enabling precise measurement of model performance.
Context & Related Work.Mode Collapse Finding: Evaluation reveals models maintain high Validity but exhibit mode collapse as hypothesis spaces grow, with Uniqueness and Recovery degrading systematically despite traditional accuracy metrics.

Results & Analysis.Reasoning Models Superior: Reasoning models consistently outperform non-reasoning models across all tasks, maintaining high Validity, Novelty, and Recovery rates, especially as task difficulty and hypothesis space size increase.
Results & Analysis.Mode Collapse Evidence: Systematic decline in Recovery Rate with increasing task difficulty reveals mode collapse, where models converge on limited hypothesis subsets despite maintaining solution validity.
Results & Analysis.Task Difficulty Impact: Performance gaps widen with difficulty: Causal Inference is most tractable, 3D Voxel intermediate, and Boolean Genetic Interaction most discriminative with sharpest coverage deficits.
Results & Analysis.Exploration Efficiency Differences: Information-theoretic analysis shows reasoning models achieve steeper entropy growth and higher information gain per query, indicating more efficient hypothesis space exploration.

Innovation Discovery.Limitation Breakthrough: Overcome the systematic degradation in Uniqueness and Recovery as the admissible hypothesis space grows, a quantitative collapse identified in the conclusion. This requires moving beyond models that merely achieve high Validity to those that can comprehensively explore and map the full set of valid explanations under increasing underdetermination.
Innovation Discovery.Methodological Improvement: Develop and integrate entropy-seeking decoding strategies or explicit memory architectures that prevent hypothesis mode collapse. This would allow the model to track and avoid previously generated hypotheses across multiple sampling rounds, directly addressing the low Uniqueness and Recovery rates observed in the study.
Innovation Discovery.Application Expansion: Apply the HypoSpace diagnostic framework to scientific domains with probabilistic or simulation-based validators, such as molecular design or ecological modeling. This would test the framework's robustness beyond the current structured domains with deterministic validators and extend its utility to more complex, real-world scientific inference problems.
Innovation Discovery.Creativity Metrics for Scientific AI: Establish a formal link between computational creativity metrics (Validity, Uniqueness, Recovery) and human scientific discovery processes. This research direction would investigate whether these metrics correlate with the utility and impact of AI-generated hypotheses in collaborative human-AI scientific workflows, moving beyond synthetic benchmarks.
Innovation Discovery.Scaling Set-Valued Hypothesis Generation: Investigate architectural and algorithmic innovations that enable LLMs to efficiently represent, navigate, and sample from exponentially large or continuous hypothesis spaces. This addresses the core challenge of underdetermination at scale, where brute-force enumeration of the admissible set becomes computationally intractable.

Context & Related Work.figure_caption: Figure 1: HypoSpace evaluation framework and model performance comparison. (a) Our diagnostic approach treats LLMs as samplers over hypothesis spaces. Given observations $O$ , models generate $N$ hypotheses that are validated for consistency with data and deduplicated for uniqueness. We measure three complementary indicators: Validity (VR: precision of valid hypotheses), Uniqueness (NR: non-redundancy among proposals), and Recovery (RR: coverage of the enumerated admissible set $\mathcal { H } _ { O }$ ). These operationalize creativity theoryâ€™s appropriateness, originality, and fluency dimensions, respectively. (b) Recovery Rate comparison across models on task of Boolean genetic interactions, showing systematic degradation as hypothesis spaces grow from simple to hard settings, with reasoning models generally outperforming non-reasoning models.
reference_text: Our approach treats LLMs as samplers that generate finite sets of candidate hypotheses (Figure 1a)

Both Uniqueness and Recovery degrade predictably with increasing $| \mathcal { H } _ { O } |$ (Figure 1b), indicating that current models tend to circle a small subset of admissible explanations rather than systematically explore the complete space that observations allow

Context & Related Work.figure_caption: Figure 2: HypoSpace task instantiations. (a) Causal inference from perturbations: Given intervention observations (e.g., perturbing node C affects nodes B), models propose causal DAGs consistent with the data. Multiple valid graph structures can explain the same perturbation patterns. (b) $3 D$ voxel reconstruction under gravity: From top-down 2D projections, models reconstruct 3D voxel structures satisfying projection constraints and gravity (stacking rules). The same projection admits multiple valid 3D configurations. (c) Boolean genetic interactions: From phenotype observations of parental combinations, models propose Boolean expressions relating inputs to outputs. Expressions that collapse to the same form under our restricted canonicalizer count as one hypothesis. Each domain exemplifies scientific underdetermination where multiple mechanistically distinct hypotheses explain identical observations, enabling measurement of Validity, Uniqueness, and Recovery across enumerated hypothesis spaces.
reference_text: We instantiate three structured diagnostics (Figure 2) that mirror common patterns of scientific inference while allowing exact enumeration of $\mathcal { H } _ { O }$ : causal graphs from perturbations, gravityconstrained 3D voxel worlds from top-down projections, and Boolean genetic interactions from phenotype observations
As in Figure 2a, let $V = \{ v _ { 1 } , \ldots , v _ { n } \}$ be labeled nodes and $G ^ { \star } = \left( V , E ^ { \star } \right)$ a latent DAG
As in Figure 2b, an observation is a binary top-down projection $V \in \{ 0 , 1 \} ^ { M \times M }$ where $V _ { i , j } = 1$ indicates at least one occupied voxel in column $( i , j )$
As in Figure 2c, inputs are maternal/paternal phenotypes $x , y \in \{ 0 , 1 \}$ and output $\pi \in$ $\{ 0 , 1 \}$

Results & Analysis.figure_caption: Table 1: HypoSpace evaluation. Performance across reasoning and non-reasoning models using three complementary metrics: Validity Rate (VR; precision of hypotheses consistent with observations), Uniqueness/Novelty Rate (NR; non-redundancy among proposals), and Recovery Rate (RR; coverage of the enumerated admissible set $\mathcal { H } _ { O }$ ). Settings scale from Difficulty level 1 (simple) to 3 (hard) with corresponding increases in hypothesis space size $| H _ { O } |$ . Results show mean $\pm$ standard deviation across instances. Reasoning models maintain high performance across all metrics, while non-reasoning models show degraded VR and consequently lower RR, particularly in harder settings with larger hypothesis spaces. We highlight the best and second-best results in the table.
reference_text: Table 1 summarizes Validity (VR), Uniqueness (NR), and Recovery (RR) across difficulty for the three diagnostics
For transparency, the instance settings are printed in the Table 1

Results & Analysis.figure_caption: Figure 3: Information-theoretic analysis of hypothesis space exploration in HypoSpace. (a) Cumulative entropy as a function of sequential queries, measuring how uncertainty reduction varies across models as they sample from the hypothesis space. Steeper curves indicate more efficient exploration of distinct valid hypotheses. (b) Information gain per query (with 0.5 vertical offset for visual clarity). The curve shape reflects each modelâ€™s marginal contribution of new information with additional samples, revealing differences in exploration strategies and susceptibility to mode collapse. Models with flatter curves show diminishing returns in hypothesis diversity, consistent with the Recovery Rate degradation observed in Table 1.
reference_text: Table 3 lists the models included in our evaluation and clarifies the access path

Results & Analysis.figure_caption: Figure 4: Failure modes and exploration patterns in HypoSpace hypothesis generation. (a) Error categorization across models: Distribution of failure types including parse failures (malformed outputs), constraint violations (structurally invalid hypotheses), invalid generations (inconsistent with observations), and duplicates (exact and canonical equivalences). Higher proportions of duplicates indicate mode collapse tendencies. (b) Hypothesis space coverage: Fraction of the enumerated admissible set $\mathcal { H } _ { O }$ explored versus unexplored by each model. Limited exploration (lower blue bars) corresponds to reduced Recovery Rates and reveals the extent to which models fail to map the full space of valid explanations, even when maintaining high Validity.
reference_text: Figure 4 decomposes the sources of limited hypothesis coverage through complementary analyses of failure types and exploration completeness

The error categorization (Figure 4a) reveals that mode collapse stems primarily from duplicate generation rather than validity failures: while parse errors and constraint violations remain relatively low across models, exact and canonical duplicates constitute the dominant failure mode, particularly for non-reasoning models

The exploration analysis (Figure 4b) quantifies this limitation directly, showing that even high-performing models like GPT-5 and Gemini-2.5-Pro explore only $60 \%$ of enumerated admissible sets, with weaker models covering substantially smaller fractions
